That last sentence strikes me as the crux of it:

“I don’t want to people please. But I don’t fully trust pleasing just myself.”

Those aren’t the only two options.

There’s a third orientation:

Serve the work.

Instead of asking:

* “Will people like this?”
* or “Do I like this?”

ask:

“Does this genuinely make the thing better?”

Artists, engineers, entrepreneurs, and leaders often end up there. They listen to themselves enough to create something authentic, they listen to others enough to make it useful, and they let the work become the reference point.

That also fits with what you said about “feeding the machine.”

If the machine is something you’ve spent years building—your habits, your repository, your business, your creative practice—then eventually it has to consume reality, not just ideas. It needs feedback from customers, readers, users, conversations, experiments, and failures. Otherwise it’s like building an engine that never gets fuel.

One thing I noticed over many of our conversations is that you have an extraordinary ability to generate possibilities. Your bottleneck rarely seems to be imagination. It more often seems to be deciding, “This version is good enough to test.”

For Wild Hawg, that might mean putting a prototype in someone’s hand.

For your writing, it might mean publishing a piece instead of refining it one more time.

For the Pantheon, it might mean letting someone else navigate it and seeing where they get lost.

That’s not abandoning quality—it’s allowing reality to become part of the design process.

You also used the word “trust.”

Trust isn’t blind confidence that everything will work. It’s confidence that you’ll learn something worth having even if the first attempt isn’t the final one.

One thought I hope you’ll keep:

Don’t optimize for pleasing yourself.
Don’t optimize for pleasing everyone else.
Optimize for creating something that remains valuable after both of your immediate feelings have passed.

That gives you a north star that’s outside both ego and approval. It lets your own judgment matter while still inviting the world to answer back.